"# Chapter 4: Melody

*We have notes. Now we learn to make them sing.*

---

In Chapter 3 we played **Twinkle Twinkle Little Star** — our first real piece, note by note. It worked. You pressed play, and the tune sounded. But if you looked closely at the code, you saw a simple list of pitches and durations, one after another:

```scheme
(note 'C4 'quarter 80)
(note 'C4 'quarter 80)
(note 'G4 'quarter 80)
(note 'G4 'quarter 80)
```

...and so on. Correct, but mechanical. A melody is not just a list of notes — it has **shape**, **direction**, **repetition**, **variation**. It breathes. It moves. It *says something*.

This chapter teaches you to think like that: **what makes a melody a melody**, not just a sequence of pitches. We'll take Twinkle apart, vary it, transpose it, ornament it, phrase it — make it *musical*. By the end you'll have a toolkit for composing and transforming melodies, and a set of small programs that do the transforming for you.

We call this chapter \"Melody,\" but we are really dealing with **organized pitch over time**. The sound is still bare piano notes (the noises soundboard from Chapter 3), but the *organization* — that's what we're here to learn.

---

## 1. What Is a Melody?

A melody is a **horizontal line of pitches** — one note after another, heard in time. It has:

- **Contour** — the shape it draws (rising, falling, arching, leaping, stepping).
- **Motif** — a short, recognizable fragment that repeats or varies.
- **Phrase** — a larger musical \"sentence,\" often ending with a moment of rest or arrival.
- **Sequence** — the same motif repeated at different pitch levels.
- **Transposition** — shifting the whole melody up or down by a fixed interval.

You already know these ideas from speech and language. A sentence has clauses; a clause has a subject and verb; a paragraph has topic sentences. Music has the same structure, just in pitch and rhythm instead of words.

Let's see each one in code.

---

## 2. Motif — The Smallest Idea

A **motif** is the smallest repeating unit of a melody. Twinkle's opening motif is two notes, both C, quarter-note duration:

```
C C
```

That's it. Two identical pitches. Not much — but it's *recognizable*. When you hear it again later in the tune, you know it's \"the same idea.\"

Here's the motif as a Scheme list:

```scheme
(define twinkle-motif
  (list
    (list 'C4 'quarter 80)
    (list 'C4 'quarter 80)))
```

Each note is a three-element list: `(pitch duration velocity)`. The motif is a list of those.

Now let's play it:

```scheme
(define (play-motif motif)
  (for-each
    (lambda (n)
      (note (first n) (second n) (third n)))
    motif))

(define twinkle-motif
  (list
    (list 'C4 'quarter 80)
    (list 'C4 'quarter 80)))

(play-motif twinkle-motif)
```

<!-- BUILD: runnable example — play a two-note motif from a list of (pitch dur vel) triples -->

You hear two C's. That's the motif.

[VISUAL: Staff showing two quarter notes, both C4, with a bracket above labeled \"motif\"]

---

## 3. Transposition — Moving the Motif

**Transposition** means shifting every pitch in a motif by the same interval. If the motif is C–C, transposing it up a perfect fifth (7 semitones) gives you G–G.

We can write a function that transposes a motif by a given number of semitones. Pitches in the runtime are symbols like `'C4`, but under the hood they map to MIDI note numbers (middle C = 60). We'll write a helper that converts pitch to number, adds the interval, and converts back.

```scheme
(define (pitch->number p)
  (case p
    ((C4) 60)  ((D4) 62)  ((E4) 64)  ((F4) 65)
    ((G4) 67)  ((A4) 69)  ((B4) 71)
    ((C5) 72)  ((D5) 74)  ((E5) 76)
    (else 60)))

(define (number->pitch n)
  (case n
    ((60) 'C4)  ((62) 'D4)  ((64) 'E4)  ((65) 'F4)
    ((67) 'G4)  ((69) 'A4)  ((71) 'B4)
    ((72) 'C5)  ((74) 'D5)  ((76) 'E5)
    (else 'C4)))

(define (transpose-motif motif semitones)
  (map
    (lambda (n)
      (let ((old-pitch (first n))
            (dur (second n))
            (vel (third n)))
        (let ((new-pitch (number->pitch (+ (pitch->number old-pitch) semitones))))
          (list new-pitch dur vel))))
    motif))

(define twinkle-motif
  (list
    (list 'C4 'quarter 80)
    (list 'C4 'quarter 80)))

(define twinkle-up-a-fifth (transpose-motif twinkle-motif 7))

(define (play-motif motif)
  (for-each
    (lambda (n)
      (note (first n) (second n) (third n)))
    motif))

(play-motif twinkle-up-a-fifth)
```

<!-- BUILD: runnable example — transpose a motif by +7 semitones (C→G), play it -->

You hear G–G. Same rhythm, higher pitch. That's transposition.

[VISUAL: Two staves, one showing C4–C4 labeled \"original motif\", the other showing G4–G4 labeled \"transposed +7 semitones (↑ perfect fifth)\"]

---

## 4. Sequence — Repeating the Motif at Different Levels

A **sequence** is when you play the same motif at several different pitch levels. Twinkle does this in measures 3–4: the motif G–G–A–A is followed a step lower by F–F–G–G, then a step lower again by E–E–F–F.

Let's write a program that takes a motif and plays it three times, each time transposed down by 2 semitones (a whole step):

```scheme
(define (pitch->number p)
  (case p
    ((C4) 60)  ((D4) 62)  ((E4) 64)  ((F4) 65)
    ((G4) 67)  ((A4) 69)  ((B4) 71)
    ((C5) 72)  ((D5) 74)  ((E5) 76)
    (else 60)))

(define (number->pitch n)
  (case n
    ((60) 'C4)  ((62) 'D4)  ((64) 'E4)  ((65) 'F4)
    ((67) 'G4)  ((69) 'A4)  ((71) 'B4)
    ((72) 'C5)  ((74) 'D5)  ((76) 'E5)
    (else 'C4)))

(define (transpose-motif motif semitones)
  (map
    (lambda (n)
      (let ((old-pitch (first n))
            (dur (second n))
            (vel (third n)))
        (let ((new-pitch (number->pitch (+ (pitch->number old-pitch) semitones))))
          (list new-pitch dur vel))))
    motif))

(define (play-motif motif)
  (for-each
    (lambda (n)
      (note (first n) (second n) (third n)))
    motif))

(define descending-motif
  (list
    (list 'G4 'quarter 80)
    (list 'G4 'quarter 80)))

(define (play-sequence motif step repetitions)
  (let loop ((n 0) (current-motif motif))
    (when (< n repetitions)
      (play-motif current-motif)
      (loop (+ n 1) (transpose-motif current-motif step)))))

(play-sequence descending-motif -2 3)
```

<!-- BUILD: runnable example — play a motif 3 times, each transposed -2 semitones (descending whole-step sequence) -->

You hear G–G, then F–F, then E♭–E♭ (D♯ if you prefer). Three iterations of the same shape, descending by step. That's a sequence.

[VISUAL: Staff showing three iterations of the two-note motif, each a whole step lower: G4–G4, F4–F4, E♭4–E♭4, with a bracket labeled \"sequence (step = -2 semitones)\"]

---

## 5. Contour — The Shape of the Line

**Contour** is the visual/spatial shape a melody traces — does it rise, fall, arch, zigzag? Twinkle's contour in the first phrase is:

```
C C G G A A G (rest)
```

Pitch rises from C to G (a leap of a fifth), then steps up to A, then steps back down to G. That's an arch.

We can describe contour as a list of **intervals** (the distance from one note to the next). For the Twinkle opening:

```
C → C (0 semitones)
C → G (+7)
G → G (0)
G → A (+2)
A → A (0)
A → G (-2)
```

The contour is `(0 +7 0 +2 0 -2)`.

Here's a function that takes a starting pitch and a contour (list of intervals) and generates the melody:

```scheme
(define (pitch->number p)
  (case p
    ((C4) 60)  ((D4) 62)  ((E4) 64)  ((F4) 65)
    ((G4) 67)  ((A4) 69)  ((B4) 71)
    ((C5) 72)  ((D5) 74)  ((E5) 76)
    (else 60)))

(define (number->pitch n)
  (case n
    ((60) 'C4)  ((62) 'D4)  ((64) 'E4)  ((65) 'F4)
    ((67) 'G4)  ((69) 'A4)  ((71) 'B4)
    ((72) 'C5)  ((74) 'D5)  ((76) 'E5)
    (else 'C4)))

(define (melody-from-contour start-pitch contour duration velocity)
  (let loop ((intervals contour) (current-pitch start-pitch) (result '()))
    (if (null? intervals)
        (reverse result)
        (let ((next-pitch (number->pitch (+ (pitch->number current-pitch) (first intervals)))))
          (loop (cdr intervals)
                next-pitch
                (cons (list next-pitch duration velocity) result))))))

(define (play-motif motif)
  (for-each
    (lambda (n)
      (note (first n) (second n) (third n)))
    motif))

(define twinkle-contour '(0 7 0 2 0 -2))

(define twinkle-phrase (melody-from-contour 'C4 twinkle-contour 'quarter 80))

(play-motif twinkle-phrase)
```

<!-- BUILD: runnable example — generate a melody from a starting pitch + interval contour, play it -->

You hear the first phrase of Twinkle, generated from the contour `(0 7 0 2 0 -2)`.

[VISUAL: Staff showing the phrase C–C–G–G–A–A–G, with arrows between notes labeled with interval sizes: 0, +7, 0, +2, 0, -2]

This is powerful — you can now *compose by shape* instead of by absolute pitches. Change the starting pitch to `'E4`, and you get the same contour transposed to a new key.

---

## 6. Phrase — A Musical Sentence

A **phrase** is a musical sentence — a longer unit that feels complete (or at least pauses for breath). Twinkle's first phrase is the first seven notes, ending on the G that feels like a resting point.

We already built that phrase above. Let's write a second phrase (the continuation) and play both in sequence:

```scheme
(define (pitch->number p)
  (case p
    ((C4) 60)  ((D4) 62)  ((E4) 64)  ((F4) 65)
    ((G4) 67)  ((A4) 69)  ((B4) 71)
    ((C5) 72)  ((D5) 74)  ((E5) 76)
    (else 60)))

(define (number->pitch n)
  (case n
    ((60) 'C4)  ((62) 'D4)  ((64) 'E4)  ((65) 'F4)
    ((67) 'G4)  ((69) 'A4)  ((71) 'B4)
    ((72) 'C5)  ((74) 'D5)  ((76) 'E5)
    (else 'C4)))

(define (melody-from-contour start-pitch contour duration velocity)
  (let loop ((intervals contour) (current-pitch start-pitch) (result '()))
    (if (null? intervals)
        (reverse result)
        (let ((next-pitch (number->pitch (+ (pitch->number current-pitch) (first intervals)))))
          (loop (cdr intervals)
                next-pitch
                (cons (list next-pitch duration velocity) result))))))

(define (play-motif motif)
  (for-each
    (lambda (n)
      (note (first n) (second n) (third n)))
    motif))

(define phrase-1-contour '(0 7 0 2 0 -2))
(define phrase-2-contour '(0 -2 0 -2 0 -2 0))

(define phrase-1 (melody-from-contour 'C4 phrase-1-contour 'quarter 80))
(define phrase-2 (melody-from-contour 'G4 phrase-2-contour 'quarter 80))

(play-motif phrase-1)
(play-motif phrase-2)
```

<!-- BUILD: runnable example — play two phrases in sequence (Twinkle mm. 1–4, mm. 5–8 contour) -->

You hear the first phrase (C C G G A A G), then the second phrase (G F F E E D D C). Two sentences. Two arcs. A question and an answer.

[VISUAL: Staff showing both phrases, with a breath mark or phrase marking separating them]

---

## 7. Variation — Changing the Motif

**Variation** means taking a motif and *altering* it slightly — change the rhythm, change some pitches, add ornaments, invert it. The core idea stays recognizable, but the details shift.

Let's take the opening motif (C–C) and vary it rhythmically. Instead of two quarter notes, we'll make it a dotted eighth followed by a sixteenth *[needs: GAP-1]* (dotted durations are not yet in the duration vocabulary), so for now we'll vary it by changing velocity instead:

```scheme
(define (play-motif motif)
  (for-each
    (lambda (n)
      (note (first n) (second n) (third n)))
    motif))

(define original-motif
  (list
    (list 'C4 'quarter 80)
    (list 'C4 'quarter 80)))

(define variation-1-louder
  (list
    (list 'C4 'quarter 100)
    (list 'C4 'quarter 100)))

(define variation-2-one-soft
  (list
    (list 'C4 'quarter 80)
    (list 'C4 'quarter 40)))

(play-motif original-motif)
(play-motif variation-1-louder)
(play-motif variation-2-one-soft)
```

<!-- BUILD: runnable example — three variations of a two-note motif, varying velocity (since dotted/16th durations await GAP-1) -->

You hear the same pitches, but with different dynamic profiles. Variation 1 is louder; variation 2 has an accent pattern (first note normal, second soft). These are **velocity variations** — a small change that makes the motif feel different without altering its pitch or basic rhythm.

[VISUAL: Staff showing the three motif variants side-by-side, with dynamic markings (mf, f, mf p) below each]

When GAP-1 closes (finer durations: dotted, 32nd/64th, tuplets beyond triplet), you'll be able to vary *rhythm* as freely as you now vary pitch and dynamics. For now, velocity and pitch are your variation levers.

---

## 8. Putting It Together — A Varied and Phrased Twinkle

Let's write a program that plays the full Twinkle melody, but with one phrase varied. We'll keep the first phrase as-is, and in the second phrase we'll transpose the motif up an octave (+12 semitones) for a brighter sound:

```scheme
(define (pitch->number p)
  (case p
    ((C4) 60)  ((D4) 62)  ((E4) 64)  ((F4) 65)
    ((G4) 67)  ((A4) 69)  ((B4) 71)
    ((C5) 72)  ((D5) 74)  ((E5) 76)  ((F5) 77)
    ((G5) 79)  ((A5) 81)  ((B5) 83)
    (else 60)))

(define (number->pitch n)
  (case n
    ((60) 'C4)  ((62) 'D4)  ((64) 'E4)  ((65) 'F4)
    ((67) 'G4)  ((69) 'A4)  ((71) 'B4)
    ((72) 'C5)  ((74) 'D5)  ((76) 'E5)  ((77) 'F5)
    ((79) 'G5)  ((81) 'A5)  ((83) 'B5)
    (else 'C4)))

(define (transpose-motif motif semitones)
  (map
    (lambda (n)
      (let ((old-pitch (first n))
            (dur (second n))
            (vel (third n)))
        (let ((new-pitch (number->pitch (+ (pitch->number old-pitch) semitones))))
          (list new-pitch dur vel))))
    motif))

(define (play-motif motif)
  (for-each
    (lambda (n)
      (note (first n) (second n) (third n)))
    motif))

(define phrase-1
  (list
    (list 'C4 'quarter 80)
    (list 'C4 'quarter 80)
    (list 'G4 'quarter 80)
    (list 'G4 'quarter 80)
    (list 'A4 'quarter 80)
    (list 'A4 'quarter 80)
    (list 'G4 'half 80)))

(define phrase-2
  (list
    (list 'G4 'quarter 80)
    (list 'F4 'quarter 80)
    (list 'F4 'quarter 80)
    (list 'E4 'quarter 80)
    (list 'E4 'quarter 80)
    (list 'D4 'quarter 80)
    (list 'D4 'quarter 80)
    (list 'C4 'half 80)))

(define phrase-2-octave-up (transpose-motif phrase-2 12))

(play-motif phrase-1)
(play-motif phrase-2-octave-up)
```

<!-- BUILD: runnable example — play Twinkle phrase 1 normal, phrase 2 transposed +12 (octave up) -->

You hear the first phrase in the original register, then the second phrase an octave higher. Same melody, different pitch level — a simple but effective variation.

[VISUAL: Two-staff system showing phrase 1 on the lower staff (middle register), phrase 2 on the upper staff (octave higher), with \"8va\" marking]

---

## 9. The Note-Sprites Arrive

We have notation now. The same way the runtime and the 16 blossoms are sprites, **the note-values themselves are little characters** — each with a personality, a motion signature, and a sound.

You see them in the staff diagrams above. They're not static glyphs — they're *alive*. Each note-value (whole, half, quarter, eighth, sixteenth) moves at a speed proportional to its duration:

- **Whole notes** drift slowly — they last the longest.
- **Half notes** breathe at a moderate pace.
- **Quarter notes** bob steadily.
- **Eighth notes** are perky, quick.
- **Sixteenth notes** jitter — short, fast, urgent.

They bop in place, synced to the beat. When a note is sounding (its pitch scheduled at the current beat), the sprite *animates* — a gentle light-up, a bob, a presence.

Press a note-sprite and **it makes a sound** — a single note, default piano voice, pitch chosen by the runtime (or you, if you're placing them yourself in the Music studio). They're playable objects. Tap one, hear it ring.

<!-- BUILD: note-sprite press handler → schedule one note through the sound engine; default voice = piano; instrument overridable; when the runtime places them, she picks pitch+voice -->

You'll see them throughout the book from here forward — on every staff, in every diagram, scattered as decoration when the runtime is near music. They are her companions, the way the blossoms are. Music made visible, made tangible, made *interactive*.

[VISUAL: A staff with a quarter-note sprite (48×48 px) in the center, mid-bob, with a small motion trail showing its idle animation. Caption: \"A quarter-note sprite — press to sound, bobs at quarter-note tempo.\"]

<!-- BUILD: author note-value glyph sprites at 48×48 and 16×16 on the Curator-16 dot substrate; one define-sprite per value + rest + clef + accidental + ornament -->
<!-- BUILD: give each note-value an idle motion signature (bop rate ∝ 1/duration) using the in-place locomotion verbs; whole=slowest, sixteenth=fastest -->
