### 22. A Pentatonic Melody—Five-Note Scale

A **pentatonic scale** has five pitches per octave (no half steps). It's common in folk music worldwide. The major pentatonic on C is **C D E G A**. Let's write a pentatonic melody:

```scheme
;; Pentatonic melody on C major pentatonic (C D E G A)
(define (pentatonic-melody)
  (note/strike 'C4 'quarter 0.8)
  (note/strike 'D4 'quarter 0.8)
  (note/strike 'E4 'quarter 0.8)
  (note/strike 'G4 'quarter 0.8)
  (note/strike 'A4 'quarter 0.8)
  (note/strike 'G4 'quarter 0.8)
  (note/strike 'E4 'quarter 0.8)
  (note/strike 'D4 'quarter 0.8)
  (note/strike 'C4 'half 0.8))

(pentatonic-melody)
```

`[VISUAL: Staff showing the pentatonic melody; no F or B pitches appear.]`

<!-- BUILD: render the pentatonic staff; on press, sound the melody -->

Pentatonic melodies sound *open* and *folk-like* because there are no half steps to create dissonance.

---


### 23. A Minor-Mode Melody—Darker Color

So far every melody has been in a **major** key (bright, happy). A **minor** key is darker. The natural minor scale on A is **A B C D E F G A**. Let's write a minor melody:

```scheme
;; A natural minor melody
(define (minor-melody)
  (note/strike 'A3 'quarter 0.8)
  (note/strike 'B3 'quarter 0.8)
  (note/strike 'C4 'quarter 0.8)
  (note/strike 'D4 'quarter 0.8)
  (note/strike 'E4 'quarter 0.8)
  (note/strike 'F4 'quarter 0.8)
  (note/strike 'E4 'quarter 0.8)
  (note/strike 'D4 'quarter 0.8)
  (note/strike 'C4 'quarter 0.8)
  (note/strike 'B3 'quarter 0.8)
  (note/strike 'A3 'half 0.8))

(minor-melody)
```

`[VISUAL: Staff showing the A natural minor melody; no sharps or flats in the key signature.]`

<!-- BUILD: render the minor-melody staff; on press, sound the melody -->

The minor mode sounds *darker*, *sadder*, or *more introspective* than major. Same melodic techniques (steps, leaps, contour), different emotional color.

---


### 24. A Whole-Tone Melody—Six-Note Scale

A **whole-tone scale** has six pitches per octave, each a whole step apart: **C D E F# G# A# C**. It sounds dreamy and *ambiguous* (no clear tonic). Let's write a whole-tone melody:

```scheme
;; Whole-tone melody
(define (whole-tone-melody)
  (note/strike 'C4 'quarter 0.8)
  (note/strike 'D4 'quarter 0.8)
  (note/strike 'E4 'quarter 0.8)
  (note/strike 'Gb4 'quarter 0.8)  ;; F#
  (note/strike 'Ab4 'quarter 0.8)  ;; G#
  (note/strike 'Bb4 'quarter 0.8)  ;; A#
  (note/strike 'C5 'half 0.8))

(whole-tone-melody)
```

`[VISUAL: Staff showing the whole-tone melody with sharps (F# G# A#).]`

<!-- BUILD: render the whole-tone staff; on press, sound the melody -->

The whole-tone scale sounds *floating* and *unanchored*—Debussy used it constantly. It has no leading tone, no strong sense of key.

---


### 25. A Melodic Ostinato—Repeating Short Pattern

An **ostinato** is a short melodic pattern repeated many times, usually in the bass. Let's write a two-bar ostinato and let it loop:

```scheme
;; Two-bar melodic ostinato
(define (melodic-ostinato)
  (note/strike 'C4 'eighth 0.7)
  (note/strike 'E4 'eighth 0.7)
  (note/strike 'G4 'eighth 0.7)
  (note/strike 'E4 'eighth 0.7)
  (note/strike 'C4 'eighth 0.7)
  (note/strike 'E4 'eighth 0.7)
  (note/strike 'G4 'eighth 0.7)
  (note/strike 'E4 'eighth 0.7))

;; Repeat it four times
(define (ostinato-loop)
  (melodic-ostinato)
  (melodic-ostinato)
  (melodic-ostinato)
  (melodic-ostinato))

(ostinato-loop)
```

`[VISUAL: Staff showing the two-bar ostinato pattern repeated four times; note-sprites bop in a tight, driving rhythm.]`

<!-- BUILD: render the ostinato loop; on press, sound all four repetitions -->

Ostinatos create *groove* and *hypnotic momentum*—common in minimalist music and bass lines.

---


### 26. A Blues Melody—Blue Notes

A **blues melody** uses *blue notes*—pitches bent or flattened for expressive effect. The blues scale on C is **C Eb F Gb G Bb C** (flattened 3rd, 5th, and 7th). Let's write a blues melody:

```scheme
;; Blues melody in C
(define (blues-melody)
  (note/strike 'C4 'quarter 0.8)
  (note/strike 'Eb4 'quarter 0.8)  ;; blue 3rd
  (note/strike 'F4 'quarter 0.8)
  (note/strike 'Gb4 'eighth 0.7)  ;; blue 5th
  (note/strike 'G4 'eighth 0.8)
  (note/strike 'Bb4 'quarter 0.8)  ;; blue 7th
  (note/strike 'C5 'half 0.8))

(blues-melody)
```

`[VISUAL: Staff showing the blues scale melody with flats on Eb, Gb, Bb.]`

<!-- BUILD: render the blues-melody staff; on press, sound the melody -->

The blue notes (Eb, Gb, Bb) create the *blues sound*—expressive, bittersweet, jazzy.

