### 27. A Call-and-Response with Variation—Developing the Answer

Let's write a call-and-response where the response *develops* the call instead of just answering it:

```scheme
;; Call: simple ascending line
(define (developed-call)
  (note/strike 'C4 'quarter 0.8)
  (note/strike 'D4 'quarter 0.8)
  (note/strike 'E4 'quarter 0.8))

;; Response: takes the call's contour and ornaments it
(define (developed-response)
  (note/strike 'E4 'eighth 0.7)
  (note/strike 'F4 'sixteenth 0.6)  ;; ornament
  (note/strike 'E4 'sixteenth 0.6)
  (note/strike 'D4 'quarter 0.8)
  (note/strike 'C4 'half 0.8))

(developed-call)
(developed-response)
```

`[VISUAL: Two staves: the call (simple C D E), the response (ornamented descent).]`

<!-- BUILD: render the developed call-and-response; on press, sound both phrases -->

The response *elaborates* the call—same basic contour, but with added ornaments and rhythm variation.

---


### 28. A Melodic Drone—Single Sustained Pitch Under a Moving Line

A **drone** is a sustained or repeating pitch (often in the bass) under a melody. Let's write a melody over a C drone:

```scheme
;; Drone: sustained C in the bass (very long duration, or looped)
(define (drone-bass)
  (note/strike 'C2 'whole 0.5)  ;; low C, sustained
  (note/strike 'C2 'whole 0.5)
  (note/strike 'C2 'whole 0.5)
  (note/strike 'C2 'whole 0.5))

;; Melody: moving line over the drone
(define (melody-over-drone)
  (note/strike 'E4 'quarter 0.8)
  (note/strike 'F4 'quarter 0.8)
  (note/strike 'G4 'quarter 0.8)
  (note/strike 'A4 'quarter 0.8)
  (note/strike 'G4 'quarter 0.8)
  (note/strike 'F4 'quarter 0.8)
  (note/strike 'E4 'quarter 0.8)
  (note/strike 'D4 'quarter 0.8)
  (note/strike 'C4 'half 0.8))

;; Play both simultaneously (engine schedules both voices)
(drone-bass)
(melody-over-drone)
```

`[VISUAL: Two staves: the bass clef showing sustained whole-note C2s, the treble clef showing the moving melody.]`

<!-- BUILD: render the drone + melody score; schedule both voices to play simultaneously; on press, sound both -->

The drone creates a *pedal point*—a harmonic anchor. The melody moves freely over it.

---


### 29. A Scalewise Run—Fast Stepwise Motion

A **scale run** is fast stepwise motion, often used as a flourish or transition. Let's write an ascending C major scale run in sixteenth notes:

```scheme
;; Ascending scale run in sixteenth notes
(define (scale-run-ascending)
  (note/strike 'C4 'sixteenth 0.8)
  (note/strike 'D4 'sixteenth 0.8)
  (note/strike 'E4 'sixteenth 0.8)
  (note/strike 'F4 'sixteenth 0.8)
  (note/strike 'G4 'sixteenth 0.8)
  (note/strike 'A4 'sixteenth 0.8)
  (note/strike 'B4 'sixteenth 0.8)
  (note/strike 'C5 'quarter 0.8))

(scale-run-ascending)
```

`[VISUAL: Staff showing a fast ascending scale run; sixteenth-note sprites bop very quickly in a straight line upward.]`

<!-- BUILD: render the scale-run staff; sixteenth-note sprites animate fast; on press, sound the run -->

Now descending:

```scheme
;; Descending scale run
(define (scale-run-descending)
  (note/strike 'C5 'sixteenth 0.8)
  (note/strike 'B4 'sixteenth 0.8)
  (note/strike 'A4 'sixteenth 0.8)
  (note/strike 'G4 'sixteenth 0.8)
  (note/strike 'F4 'sixteenth 0.8)
  (note/strike 'E4 'sixteenth 0.8)
  (note/strike 'D4 'sixteenth 0.8)
  (note/strike 'C4 'quarter 0.8))

(scale-run-descending)
```

`[VISUAL: Staff showing a descending scale run.]`

<!-- BUILD: render the descending scale-run staff; on press, sound the run -->

Scale runs are *virtuosic*—they show off technical skill and create excitement.

