### 30. A Trilled Cadence—Rapid Alternation Between Two Pitches

A **trill** rapidly alternates between a main pitch and the pitch one step above. Let's trill on G (alternating G–A) before resolving to C:

```scheme
;; Trill on G (G–A alternation) then resolve to C
(define (trilled-cadence)
  (note/strike 'G4 'sixteenth 0.8)
  (note/strike 'A4 'sixteenth 0.8)
  (note/strike 'G4 'sixteenth 0.8)
  (note/strike 'A4 'sixteenth 0.8)
  (note/strike 'G4 'sixteenth 0.8)
  (note/strike 'A4 'sixteenth 0.8)
  (note/strike 'G4 'sixteenth 0.8)
  (note/strike 'A4 'sixteenth 0.8)
  (note/strike 'C5 'half 0.8))  ;; resolve

(trilled-cadence)
```

`[VISUAL: Staff showing the G–A trill (eight sixteenths) with a trill symbol above, then a half-note C5.]`

<!-- BUILD: render the trilled-cadence staff; when GAP-2 closes, show the trill symbol; on press, sound the trill + resolution -->

The trill creates *tension* and *ornamentation* before the final resolution to C.

